Dusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1312<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/22/03 1:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lets build a small, reusable spaceplane</span><hr size=1> A shielded reactor is not feasable.<br>
<br>
The NB-36 nuclear airplane (which carried a nuclear reactor for tests, but not for power) carried some 20 TONS of shielding. After landing, the reactor was remotely lowered into an underground pit.<br>
<br>
&quot;... For the reactor tests, officials chose a B-36H at Carswell that had been seriously damaged when a tornado swept through the base in 1952. It needed a new nose section, and since the test aircraft's cockpit area would have to be completely modified, it made sense to use an aircraft that was already scheduled for a nose job. Engineers replaced the standard pressurized crew compartment with a 12<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>-ton, self-contained capsule lined with lead and rubber. Behind that sat a four-ton lead disc that bisected the fuselage, along with waterfilled sections to absorb stray radiation.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Of the crew, only the pilot and co-pilot could see the outside world, and they viewed it through a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>leaded glass windshield nine to 11 inches thick.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
The reason for all the shielding was the 35,000-pound test reactor, stored in a special underground &quot;pit&quot; between flights. Before each mission, a hydraulic cradle raised the reactor into a special compartment in the plane's aft bomb bay. Large intake scoops ducted air to the reactor for cooling in flight. &quot;<br>
<br>
Here's more:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.ufx.org/nepa/nepa3.htm">www.ufx.org/nepa/nepa3.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
There is no way to use a nuclear craft in any &quot;normal&quot; environment.<br>
<br>
In fact there is no way to use ANY nuclear-reactor powered launcher. Due to the incredible hazard in a flying critical reactor, there is a formal set of UN Principles which prohibit their use. The US <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>explicitly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> adheres to those rules and has structured Project Prometheus in accordance with these international guidlines.<br>
<br>
Other systems, like Orion, are simply illegal.<br>
<br>
<br>
Yale<br>
<br>
BTW... the rocket in the link by DL is technically flawed beyond any possiblity of reality (even if one would risk flying a critical reactor rocket thru the biosphere)<br>
