They said that it was impossible to build a steam ship to cross the Atlantic, Brunell proved them wrong with the Great Britain.<br>
<br>
They then said that it was impossible to build a non-stop steam ship to sail to Australia. Then, in 1858 Brunell built the great Eastern and proved them wrong again (this monster was just short of 700 feet long and dwarved other ships at the time, nothing larger as seen until 1901)<br>
<br>
They said heavier than air powered flight was impossible, then the Wright brothers flew, <br>
<br>
Liberty ship *is* Science Fiction, in so far as the concept takes currently established technologies and stretches them somewhat, but it is not science fantasy (Like stargates) I have little doubt that the technical problems, though daunting, can be overcome inorder to build her (or something like her)<br>
<br>
<br>
Perhaps Liberty ships biggest problem isn’t technical at all. It may have the same problem as Brunell had with the Great Eastern, at least to start with. IE that there may not be enough loads in the 1000 ton category to make it pay.<br>
<br>
In any case a small crew transfer/light cargo SSTO is essential, whatever else we do, larger vessels are pretty much useless without it.<br>
